Note:
HIR -> F# Backend - Source-to-source F# generation from HIR.

This is the canonical single-file HIR-walking backend for F#, mirroring the
shape of hir_to_lua.runa and hir_to_ruby.runa: it walks the HIR the F#
frontend (fsharp_to_hir.runa) produces and emits idiomatic F# source text.
There is deliberately NO HIR optimization or validation pass here - those are
compiler middle-end concerns, not a source-to-source backend's, and including
them would both duplicate middle-end logic and corrupt the round-trip identity
this backend is built to preserve.

CRITICAL - which HIR model this backend consumes:
The F# frontend does NOT use the typed hir_nodes.runa (17xxx) producer model
that the Lua/Ruby frontends use. It uses the hir.runa core model (node-type
constants 10000-13xxx) built via create_hir_node / set_hir_node_value /
add_hir_node, and for the compound expression/statement shapes it allocates
arena "composite" records whose FIRST slot (offset 0) holds a pointer to the
canonical 104-byte base HIRNode and whose subsequent slots hold the shape's
operand pointers at fixed offsets. The frontend itself disambiguates a
composite from a bare base node by testing whether slot 0 is a pointer
(>= 65536) versus a small node-type constant; this backend reads nodes using
exactly that same convention (see fs_base / fs_kind below) so it consumes
precisely what the frontend emits.

Composite record offsets (slot 0 = base HIRNode pointer in every case):
  HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION 10002: op@8  left@16  right@24
  HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION   10005: callee@8  arguments(List)@16  argc@24
  HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION 10014: parameters(List)@8  paramc@16  body@24
  HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT   11005: expr@8  arms(List)@24  armc@32
  HIR_IF_STATEMENT      11003: cond@8  then@16  else@24
  HIR_TRY_STATEMENT     11015: try@8  catches(List)@16  catchc@24  finally@32
  HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT   11008: cond@8  body@16
  HIR_FOR_STATEMENT     11007: itervar(token)@8  iterable@16  body@32
  HIR_LET_STATEMENT     11000: var_name(string)@8  var_type@24  init@32  is_rec@40
  HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE       11006: pattern@8  guard@16  body@24

Bare base HIRNodes (value@40, value_type@48, children list@24, child_count@32):
  HIR_LITERAL 10000, HIR_IDENTIFIER 10001, HIR_INTERPOLATED_STRING 10009,
  HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL 10011, HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL 10012, HIR_RECORD_LITERAL 10013,
  HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT 11018, HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION 12001, HIR_RECORD_TYPE 13008,
  HIR_ENUM_TYPE 13019, HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION 12006, HIR_VARIANT_DEFINITION 12007,
  the pattern kinds 14000-14010, and the typed type nodes (HIR_TYPE_REF /
  HIR_FUNCTION_TYPE / HIR_GENERIC_TYPE / HIR_TUPLE_TYPE) the frontend builds
  via the hir_nodes.runa type producers and reads back with the matching
  hir_get_* type accessors. The module root is HIR_MODULE (17000) carrying its
  declarations in the children slot.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/fsharp/fsharp_emitter.runa" as Emitter
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/fsharp/fsharp_lexer.runa" as FSharpLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIRNodes
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Code Generation Context
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Threads the entire HIR-to-F# generation through one struct so emission helpers
manage nested indentation and accumulate errors without positional plumbing.
hir_module is the module root; indent_level is bumped by indent/dedent and
rendered through the emitter's fsharp_indent_string; errors collects messages
and had_error short-circuits nothing destructive but is exposed for the driver
to inspect.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Idiomatic value-of-type struct: construction allocates the heap home directly
and the binding is the struct pointer. Helpers re-bind the pointer with a
typed Let; field mutations write in place.
@End Implementation
Type called "FSharpCodeGenContext":
    hir_module as Integer          Note: HIR module root being generated from
    indent_level as Integer        Note: Current indentation level
    errors as Integer              Note: List of generation error messages
    had_error as Integer           Note: 1 if a generation error occurred
End Type

@Reasoning:
The driver hands us only the HIR module pointer. Indent starts at 0. The errors
list is eagerly created so emit helpers never null-check before appending.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_codegen_context" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be a value of type FSharpCodeGenContext with
        hir_module as hir_module,
        indent_level as 0,
        errors as proc list_create from List,
        had_error as 0

    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recording an error appends the message and flips the had_error sentinel so the
driver can report generation failures without the emitter producing partial
corrupt output mid-stream.
@End Reasoning
Process called "codegen_error" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, message as String:
    Let ctx as FSharpCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    proc list_append from List with ctx.errors, message
    Set ctx.had_error to 1
End Process

Process called "indent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer:
    Let ctx as FSharpCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
End Process

Process called "dedent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer:
    Let ctx as FSharpCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    If ctx.indent_level is greater than 0:
        Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
    End If
End Process

Process called "get_indent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx as FSharpCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return proc fsharp_indent_string from Emitter with ctx.indent_level
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Node-model accessors (the F# frontend's hir.runa dual model)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A node produced by the F# frontend is either a bare canonical HIRNode (its
slot 0 is a small node-type constant) or an arena composite record (its slot 0
is a POINTER to the base HIRNode). The frontend distinguishes them with the
threshold test "slot 0 >= 65536 means pointer"; every HIR node-type constant
this backend reasons about is far below 65536 and every live heap pointer is
far above it, so the test is exact. fs_base returns the canonical base HIRNode
in both cases, which is the node carrying the type tag, the value slot, the
children list and the metadata dictionary.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fs_base" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let slot0 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    If slot0 is greater than or equal to 65536:
        Note: composite record - slot 0 is the base HIRNode pointer
        Return slot0
    End If
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
The node kind is the type tag on the base HIRNode (offset 0). Routing through
fs_base first means callers may pass either a bare node or a composite record
and always recover the correct kind.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fs_kind" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc fs_base with node
    Return proc get_hir_node_type from HIR with base
End Process

@Reasoning:
The value payload (string pointer / int64 / float bits / boolean) lives on the
base HIRNode at offset 40, written by set_hir_node_value. Reading through
fs_base keeps the access correct for any composite that also carries a base
value; only bare nodes use the value slot, and fs_base resolves to the base
for both shapes so the read is always against the canonical value field.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fs_value" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc fs_base with node
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base, 40
End Process

@Reasoning:
The value_type tag (offset 48) classifies the value slot payload as string(1),
boolean(2), integer(3), float(4) or null(0); the literal emitter switches on it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fs_value_type" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc fs_base with node
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base, 48
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bare nodes store their children list at base offset 24 with the count at 32.
Returning the list pointer (0 when no children were ever added) lets callers
use the List API directly; fs_child_count returns the count for loop bounds.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fs_children" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc fs_base with node
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base, 24
End Process

Process called "fs_child_count" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc list_length from List with children
End Process

@Reasoning:
Composite records hold their operand pointers at fixed slot offsets on the
COMPOSITE pointer (not the base). This helper reads slot off the composite
record directly; callers pass the composite (the value returned by the parent's
children list, which is the composite itself, not its base).
@End Reasoning
Process called "fs_slot" takes node as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, offset
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Central dispatch from HIR node kind to a specialized F# expression generator.
Literals and identifiers are checked first (the common cases). Unknown kinds
record an error and return empty string so the caller still produces parseable
output. The dispatch keys on fs_kind so both bare nodes and composite records
route correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return "()"
    End If

    Let kind be proc fs_kind with node

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_literal with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Let name be proc fs_value with node
        Return name
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION:
        Return proc generate_binary_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION:
        Return proc generate_call_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION:
        Return proc generate_lambda_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_list_literal with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_tuple_literal with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_RECORD_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_record_literal with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_INTERPOLATED_STRING:
        Return proc generate_interpolated_string with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT:
        Return proc generate_match_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IF_STATEMENT:
        Return proc generate_if_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT:
        Return proc generate_block_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_TRY_STATEMENT:
        Return proc generate_try_statement with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT:
        Return proc generate_while_statement with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR_STATEMENT:
        Return proc generate_for_statement with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
        Return proc generate_let_inline with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    proc codegen_error with ctx_ptr, "Unknown F# expression kind"
    Return "()"
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# literal rendering switches on the value_type tag: integers and floats render
their numeric text, strings render quoted+escaped, booleans render true/false
(F# keywords), and the null/unit kind renders "()" (F# unit) - the canonical
representation the frontend assigns to F# unit and null literals alike.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let vt be proc fs_value_type with node
    Let v be proc fs_value with node

    If vt is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_LITERAL_KIND_INTEGER:
        Return proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with v
    End If

    If vt is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_LITERAL_KIND_FLOAT:
        Return proc float_to_string from StringUtils with v, 6, 0
    End If

    If vt is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_LITERAL_KIND_STRING:
        Let escaped be proc escape_fsharp_string from Emitter with v
        Let quoted be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "\"", escaped
        Set quoted to proc string_concat from StringUtils with quoted, "\""
        Return quoted
    End If

    If vt is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_LITERAL_KIND_BOOLEAN:
        If v is equal to 1:
            Return "true"
        End If
        Return "false"
    End If

    Note: value_type 0 is the null / unit kind; F# unit literal is ()
    Return "()"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary expressions emit "left OP right" with single-space padding. The operator
is the raw F# lexer token stored at composite slot 8; map_fsharp_operator turns
it into the F# operator spelling. We do not parenthesize: the HIR tree already
encodes F# precedence by construction (the parser built it that way), so adding
parentheses would be redundant and would perturb the round-trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let operator be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let left_node be proc fs_slot with node, 16
    Let right_node be proc fs_slot with node, 24

    Let left_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, left_node
    Let right_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, right_node
    Let op_str be proc fsharp_operator_spelling with operator

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with left_code, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, op_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, right_code

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Call / application
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# application is space-separated, curried: "callee arg1 arg2". The frontend
materializes an F# application chain as a single CallExpression whose arguments
list holds the applied arguments in order; we re-emit the curried space-applied
form. Each argument that is itself a non-trivial expression is wrapped in
parentheses so that "f (g x) y" round-trips rather than collapsing to the
ambiguous "f g x y". A literal or identifier argument needs no parentheses.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let callee_node be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let args_list be proc fs_slot with node, 16

    Note: The F# frontend models an infix operator application "a + b" as a call
    Note: whose callee is an identifier named with the operator symbol and exactly
    Note: two arguments. To round-trip faithfully we re-emit such a call in its
    Note: infix form "a + b" (which re-parses to the same call), rather than the
    Note: prefix "+ a b" which is not the surface form the parser accepts.
    Let argc be 0
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Set argc to proc list_length from List with args_list
    End If

    If argc is equal to 2:
        Let callee_kind be proc fs_kind with callee_node
        If callee_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
            Let callee_name be proc fs_value with callee_node
            Let is_op be proc fsharp_is_operator_symbol with callee_name
            If is_op is equal to 1:
                Let lhs be proc list_get from List with args_list, 0
                Let rhs be proc list_get from List with args_list, 1
                Let lhs_code be proc generate_argument with ctx_ptr, lhs
                Let rhs_code be proc generate_argument with ctx_ptr, rhs
                Let infix be proc string_concat from StringUtils with lhs_code, " "
                Set infix to proc string_concat from StringUtils with infix, callee_name
                Set infix to proc string_concat from StringUtils with infix, " "
                Set infix to proc string_concat from StringUtils with infix, rhs_code
                Return infix
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let callee_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, callee_node
    Let result be callee_code

    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than argc:
            Let arg_node be proc list_get from List with args_list, i
            Let arg_code be proc generate_argument with ctx_ptr, arg_node
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, arg_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A callee identifier name is an F# infix operator symbol when it is one of the
symbolic operators the frontend produces as operator-named call callees. We match
the exact operator spellings ("+" "-" "*" "/" "%" "**" "=" "<>" "<" ">" "<=" ">="
"&&" "||" "|>" "<|" ">>" "<<" "@" "::") so an ordinary identifier callee (a real
function name) is never mis-rendered as infix. The check is a string-equality
cascade because the set is small and fixed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fsharp_is_operator_symbol" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let symbols be a list containing "+", "-", "*", "/", "%", "**", "=", "<>", "<", ">", "<=", ">=", "&&", "||", "|>", "<|", ">>", "<<", "@", "::"
    Let count be proc list_length from List with symbols
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let sym be proc list_get from List with symbols, i
        Let eq be proc string_equals from StringCore with name, sym
        If eq is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
An application argument is parenthesized unless it is an atom (identifier or
literal) for which F#'s left-associative application already groups correctly.
Compound arguments (calls, binary expressions, lambdas, matches, ifs, literals
of collection kinds) must be parenthesized so currying boundaries survive the
round-trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_argument" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let kind be proc fs_kind with node
    Let code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, node

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        Return code
    End If
    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Return code
    End If

    Let wrapped be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "(", code
    Set wrapped to proc string_concat from StringUtils with wrapped, ")"
    Return wrapped
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lambda
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# lambdas are "fun p1 p2 -> body". Parameters are the composite's parameter
list (each entry an HIR pattern node); we render each parameter via the pattern
emitter so destructuring parameters round-trip. The body is a single expression
(F# lambda bodies are expressions), emitted inline.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_lambda_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let params_list be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let body_node be proc fs_slot with node, 24

    Let result be "fun"

    If params_list is not equal to 0:
        Let pc be proc list_length from List with params_list
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than pc:
            Let param_node be proc list_get from List with params_list, i
            Let param_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, param_node
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, param_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " -> "
    Let body_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, body_node
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Collection literals
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The frontend lowers BOTH F# lists [a; b] and arrays [|a; b|] to HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL
(it cannot preserve the distinction in the node kind), so the backend emits the
canonical F# list form "[a; b; c]" with semicolon separators. This round-trips
through the frontend identically because the re-parse lowers the emitted list
back to the same HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL node with the same element count.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let elements be proc fs_children with node
    Let result be "["

    If elements is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from List with elements
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let elem be proc list_get from List with elements, i
            Let elem_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, elem
            If i is greater than 0:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "; "
            End If
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, elem_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "]"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# tuples are comma-separated parenthesized "(a, b, c)". Element ordering and
arity are preserved exactly (tuples of different arity are distinct types in F#).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_tuple_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let elements be proc fs_children with node
    Let result be "("

    If elements is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from List with elements
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let elem be proc list_get from List with elements, i
            Let elem_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, elem
            If i is greater than 0:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
            End If
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, elem_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# record construction is "{ Field1 = v1; Field2 = v2 }". Each child is an
HIR_FIELD_INITIALIZER node from which we read the field name (a string in the
field-init's "name" property) and the value expression (its "value" property),
emitting "Name = value" entries separated by "; ".
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_record_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let fields be proc fs_children with node
    Let result be "{ "

    If fields is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from List with fields
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let field be proc list_get from List with fields, i
            Let fname be proc hir_get_field_init_name from HIRNodes with field
            Let fvalue be proc hir_get_field_init_value from HIRNodes with field
            Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, fvalue

            If i is greater than 0:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "; "
            End If
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, fname
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " }"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
The frontend stores an interpolated string as a node whose children alternate
HIR_LITERAL string segments and arbitrary hole expressions in source order. F#
interpolated strings are $"...{expr}...": we emit the $"-prefixed opener, copy
each literal segment's text verbatim into the string body, and wrap each hole
expression in {braces}. The format spec (when the frontend attached the
"format_spec" metadata) is appended after a colon inside the braces, matching
F#'s {expr:format} interpolation syntax.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_interpolated_string" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let parts be proc fs_children with node
    Let result be "$\""

    If parts is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from List with parts
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let part be proc list_get from List with parts, i
            Let part_kind be proc fs_kind with part
            If part_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
                Let seg be proc fs_value with part
                Let escaped be proc escape_fsharp_string from Emitter with seg
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, escaped
            Otherwise:
                Let hole_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, part
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "{"
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, hole_code
                Let spec be proc hir_get_metadata from HIRNodes with part, "format_spec"
                If spec is not equal to 0:
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ":"
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, spec
                End If
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "}"
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\""
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Match expression
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# match is "match expr with | pat -> body | pat -> body". The discriminant is
the match composite's expression slot (8); the arms list (slot 24) holds
HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE composites each carrying a pattern, an optional guard, and a
body. Each arm is emitted on its own indented line as "| pattern [when guard]
-> body" so the layout-sensitive F# match round-trips.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_match_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let expr_node be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let arms be proc fs_slot with node, 24

    Let expr_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "match ", expr_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " with"

    If arms is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from List with arms
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let arm be proc list_get from List with arms, i
            Let arm_code be proc generate_match_arm with ctx_ptr, arm
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
            Let arm_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, arm_indent
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, arm_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A WHEN_CLAUSE composite stores pattern@8, guard@16 (0 when absent), body@24.
We emit "| pattern [when guard] -> body". The pattern routes through the
pattern emitter (so constructor/tuple/list/record patterns round-trip) and the
guard and body route through the expression emitter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_match_arm" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let pattern_node be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let guard_node be proc fs_slot with node, 16
    Let body_node be proc fs_slot with node, 24

    Let pattern_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, pattern_node
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "| ", pattern_code

    If guard_node is not equal to 0:
        Let guard_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, guard_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " when "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, guard_code
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " -> "
    Let body_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, body_node
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pattern Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Patterns are bare HIRNodes carrying the bound name / type name in the value slot
(string) and sub-patterns in the children list. The dispatch covers every F#
pattern shape the frontend produces: identifier (variable binding), wildcard,
variant (discriminated-union constructor), tuple, array/list, record, guard,
type-test, and or-patterns. The renderings match F# pattern syntax exactly so a
re-parse reconstructs the same pattern kind.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return "_"
    End If

    Let kind be proc fs_kind with node

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER_PATTERN:
        Let name be proc fs_value with node
        If name is equal to 0:
            Return "_"
        End If
        Note: a record-field-pattern reuses identifier-pattern with a child
        Note: sub-pattern; render "Name = subpat" when a sub-pattern is present
        Let pc be proc fs_child_count with node
        If pc is greater than 0:
            Let children be proc fs_children with node
            Let sub be proc list_get from List with children, 0
            Let sub_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, sub
            Let res be proc string_concat from StringUtils with name, " = "
            Set res to proc string_concat from StringUtils with res, sub_code
            Return res
        End If
        Return name
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_WILDCARD_PATTERN:
        Return "_"
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_literal with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_VARIANT_PATTERN:
        Return proc generate_variant_pattern with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_TUPLE_PATTERN:
        Return proc generate_tuple_pattern with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_ARRAY_PATTERN:
        Return proc generate_list_pattern with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_RECORD_PATTERN:
        Return proc generate_record_pattern with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_GUARD_PATTERN:
        Return proc generate_guard_pattern with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_TYPE_PATTERN:
        Return proc generate_type_pattern with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_OR_PATTERN:
        Return proc generate_or_pattern with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    proc codegen_error with ctx_ptr, "Unknown F# pattern kind"
    Return "_"
End Process

@Reasoning:
A discriminated-union constructor pattern is "Name" (nullary) or
"Name (subpat1, subpat2)" (with arguments). The constructor name is the value
slot; the sub-patterns are the children. A single sub-pattern emits "Name subpat"
(F#'s single-argument constructor form needs no parens); multiple sub-patterns
emit the parenthesized comma form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_variant_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let name be proc fs_value with node
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node

    If count is equal to 0:
        Return name
    End If

    If count is equal to 1:
        Let sub be proc list_get from List with children, 0
        Let sub_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, sub
        Let res be proc string_concat from StringUtils with name, " "
        Set res to proc string_concat from StringUtils with res, sub_code
        Return res
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with name, " ("
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let sub be proc list_get from List with children, i
        Let sub_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, sub
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, sub_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# tuple patterns are comma-separated "(p1, p2, p3)" mirroring tuple values.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_tuple_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    Let result be "("
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let sub be proc list_get from List with children, i
        Let sub_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, sub
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, sub_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# list patterns are semicolon-separated "[p1; p2]" mirroring list values.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    Let result be "["
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let sub be proc list_get from List with children, i
        Let sub_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, sub
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "; "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, sub_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "]"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# record patterns are "{ Field1 = p1; Field2 = p2 }". Each child is an
identifier-pattern carrying the field name in its value slot and the field's
sub-pattern as its own child; generate_pattern already renders that
identifier-pattern-with-child as "Name = subpat", so we just wrap the children
in the record-pattern braces.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_record_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    Let result be "{ "
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let sub be proc list_get from List with children, i
        Let sub_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, sub
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "; "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, sub_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " }"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A guard pattern wraps an inner pattern (child 0) and a guard expression (child 1).
At the F# match-arm level the guard is rendered via the "when" clause, but the
frontend can also produce a standalone HIR_GUARD_PATTERN; we render it as
"innerpat when guardexpr" which is exactly how F# spells a guarded pattern in
arm position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_guard_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    If count is less than 2:
        If count is equal to 1:
            Let only be proc list_get from List with children, 0
            Return proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, only
        End If
        Return "_"
    End If
    Let inner be proc list_get from List with children, 0
    Let guard be proc list_get from List with children, 1
    Let inner_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, inner
    Let guard_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, guard
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with inner_code, " when "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, guard_code
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A type-test pattern is F#'s ":? TypeName [as binder]". The tested type name is
the value slot; an optional binder is child 0 (an identifier pattern). We emit
":? TypeName" and append " as binder" when the binder child is present.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_type_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let type_name be proc fs_value with node
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with ":? ", type_name

    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    If count is greater than 0:
        Let children be proc fs_children with node
        Let binder be proc list_get from List with children, 0
        Let binder_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, binder
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " as "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, binder_code
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
An or-pattern is F#'s "p1 | p2 | p3": alternatives separated by " | ". The
children are the alternatives in source order.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_or_pattern" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let alt be proc list_get from List with children, i
        Let alt_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, alt
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " | "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, alt_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: If / Block / Try / While / For (expression position)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# "if c then t else e" is an expression. The frontend stores cond@8, then@16,
else@24 (0 when the source had no else). We emit the single-line expression
form; when there is no else branch we still emit "else ()" so the if has unit
in both arms, which the frontend re-lowers to the same if shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let cond_node be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let then_node be proc fs_slot with node, 16
    Let else_node be proc fs_slot with node, 24

    Let cond_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, cond_node
    Let then_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, then_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "if ", cond_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " then "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, then_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " else "

    If else_node is not equal to 0:
        Let else_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, else_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, else_code
    Otherwise:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "()"
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A block (F# "let ... in body" sequence) is the frontend's BLOCK_STATEMENT whose
children are the let bindings followed by the trailing body expression. Each
binding renders as a "let name = init in" line; the final non-binding child is
the block's value. We emit each item on its own indented line and join them with
F#'s newline-sequenced layout, which round-trips through the layout-aware parser.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node

    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc list_get from List with children, i
        Let child_kind be proc fs_kind with child
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
            Let line_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, line_indent
        End If
        If child_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
            Let binding_code be proc generate_let_inline with ctx_ptr, child
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, binding_code
        Otherwise:
            Let expr_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, child
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, expr_code
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
An inline let-binding (inside a block or as an expression-position let) renders
as "let [rec] name = init". The variable name is composite slot 8, the
initializer slot 32, and the recursive flag slot 40 (1 when the source was
"let rec"). The "in" keyword is omitted because F#'s lightweight (offside)
syntax sequences bindings by layout, and the block emitter places each binding
on its own line.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_let_inline" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let var_name be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let init_node be proc fs_slot with node, 32
    Let is_rec be proc fs_slot with node, 40

    Let result be "let "
    If is_rec is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "rec "
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, var_name

    If init_node is not equal to 0:
        Let init_code be proc generate_function_or_value with ctx_ptr, init_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, init_code
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
An F# "let f x y = body" binding lowers in the frontend to a let whose
initializer is a LAMBDA expression. To round-trip the curried function-binding
form (rather than "let f = fun x y -> body") we detect a lambda initializer and
splice its parameters directly after the bound name: "let f x y = body". A
non-lambda initializer renders as the plain "= value" value binding.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function_or_value" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let kind be proc fs_kind with node

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION:
        Let params_list be proc fs_slot with node, 8
        Let body_node be proc fs_slot with node, 24

        Let result be ""
        If params_list is not equal to 0:
            Let pc be proc list_length from List with params_list
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than pc:
                Let param_node be proc list_get from List with params_list, i
                Let param_code be proc generate_pattern with ctx_ptr, param_node
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, param_code
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
        Note: A match (or other multi-line) body must be indented one level beyond
        Note: the binding so the F# offside rule keeps the arms inside the binding's
        Note: scope; we push indentation around the body emission so the match arms
        Note: align under the "let" rather than at column 0 (which would re-parse as
        Note: a new top-level declaration).
        proc indent with ctx_ptr
        Let body_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, body_node
        proc dedent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code
        Return result
    End If

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Let res be proc string_concat from StringUtils with " = ", value_code
    Return res
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# "try body with | pat -> handler" / "try body finally cleanup". The composite
stores try@8, catches(List)@16, finally@32. We emit the with-form when there are
catch clauses and the finally-form when there is a finally block; both may be
present, in which case the with-block is emitted first. Each catch clause is an
HIR_CATCH node read through the catch accessors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_try_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let try_body be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let catches be proc fs_slot with node, 16
    Let finally_node be proc fs_slot with node, 32

    Let body_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, try_body
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "try ", body_code

    Let catch_count be 0
    If catches is not equal to 0:
        Set catch_count to proc list_length from List with catches
    End If

    If catch_count is greater than 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " with"
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than catch_count:
            Let catch be proc list_get from List with catches, i
            Let catch_code be proc generate_catch_clause with ctx_ptr, catch
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
            Let ci be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ci
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, catch_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    If finally_node is not equal to 0:
        Let finally_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, finally_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
        Let fi be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, fi
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "finally "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, finally_code
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
An HIR_CATCH carries an exception type name, an optional bound variable, and a
body, read through the canonical catch accessors. F# spells a handler arm as
"| :? ExnType as var -> body" when a type is given, or "| var -> body" / "| _ ->
body" otherwise. We reconstruct the closest F# handler-arm spelling that the
frontend re-lowers to the same catch shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_catch_clause" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let exn_type be proc hir_get_catch_type from HIRNodes with node
    Let exn_var be proc hir_get_catch_variable from HIRNodes with node
    Let body be proc hir_get_catch_body from HIRNodes with node

    Let result be "| "

    If exn_type is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ":? "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, exn_type
        If exn_var is not equal to 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " as "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, exn_var
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If exn_var is not equal to 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, exn_var
        Otherwise:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "_"
        End If
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " -> "
    Let body_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, body
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# "while cond do body". The composite stores cond@8, body@16. We emit the
single-line "while cond do body" form which re-parses to the same while shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_while_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let cond_node be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let body_node be proc fs_slot with node, 16

    Let cond_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, cond_node
    Let body_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, body_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "while ", cond_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " do "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# "for x in iterable do body". The composite stores the iterator-variable token
at slot 8 (a raw F# lexer token whose text is the loop variable name), the
iterable expression at slot 16, and the body at slot 32. We recover the loop
variable name from the token text and emit the for-in form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_for_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let var_token be proc fs_slot with node, 8
    Let iterable_node be proc fs_slot with node, 16
    Let body_node be proc fs_slot with node, 32

    Let var_name be proc fsharp_token_text with var_token
    Let iterable_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, iterable_node
    Let body_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, body_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "for ", var_name
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " in "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, iterable_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " do "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Expression Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Type expressions in val signatures, record field types and union payloads are
the typed type nodes the frontend builds via the hir_nodes.runa type producers:
HIR_TYPE_REF (named type, name in "name" property), HIR_FUNCTION_TYPE (arrow,
parameter-types list + return type), HIR_GENERIC_TYPE (base name + argument
list), HIR_TUPLE_TYPE (element list). We render the F# spellings: named type as
its name, function type as "a -> b", generic as "Base<args>", tuple as
"a * b * c".
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_type_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let kind be proc fs_kind with node

    If kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_TYPE_REF:
        Let name be proc hir_get_type_ref_name from HIRNodes with node
        Return name
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_FUNCTION_TYPE:
        Let params be proc hir_get_function_type_params from HIRNodes with node
        Let ret be proc hir_get_function_type_return from HIRNodes with node
        Let result be ""
        If params is not equal to 0:
            Let pc be proc list_length from List with params
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than pc:
                Let p be proc list_get from List with params, i
                Let p_code be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, p
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, p_code
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " -> "
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Let ret_code be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, ret
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ret_code
        Return result
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_GENERIC_TYPE:
        Let base be proc hir_get_generic_base from HIRNodes with node
        Let args be proc hir_get_generic_args from HIRNodes with node
        Let result be base
        If args is not equal to 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "<"
            Let ac be proc list_length from List with args
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than ac:
                Let a be proc list_get from List with args, i
                Let a_code be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, a
                If i is greater than 0:
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
                End If
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, a_code
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ">"
        End If
        Return result
    End If

    Note: HIR_TUPLE_TYPE: elements are children of the tuple-type node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    If count is greater than 0:
        Let children be proc fs_children with node
        Let result be ""
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let el be proc list_get from List with children, i
            Let el_code be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, el
            If i is greater than 0:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " * "
            End If
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, el_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Return result
    End If

    Return ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Declaration Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level declaration dispatch. The frontend produces these top-level kinds:
HIR_LET_STATEMENT (let binding / function), HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION (record /
discriminated union / class / interface body), HIR_IMPORT (open directive),
HIR_VARIABLE (val signature), and HIR_MODULE (nested module/namespace). Each is
emitted as a standalone top-level F# declaration on its own line.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_declaration" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let kind be proc fs_kind with node

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
        Let indent_str be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Let body be proc generate_let_inline with ctx_ptr, node
        Let line be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_str, body
        Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, "\n"
        Return line
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIR.HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION:
        Return proc generate_type_definition with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_IMPORT:
        Let indent_str be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Let name be proc fs_value with node
        Let line be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_str, "open "
        Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, name
        Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, "\n"
        Return line
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_VARIABLE:
        Return proc generate_val_signature with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    If kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_MODULE:
        Return proc generate_nested_module with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    Note: any other top-level node is treated as an expression statement
    Let indent_str be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let expr_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, node
    Let line be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_str, expr_code
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, "\n"
    Return line
End Process

@Reasoning:
A "val" signature declares a value's type without a body: F# "val name : type".
The variable node carries the name in its value slot and the declared type as
its first child (a type node). When no type child is present we still emit
"val name : obj" so the declaration is well-formed; the frontend re-lowers it to
the same HIR_VARIABLE shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_val_signature" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let indent_str be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let name be proc fs_value with node

    Let line be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_str, "val "
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, " : "

    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    If count is greater than 0:
        Let children be proc fs_children with node
        Let type_node be proc list_get from List with children, 0
        Let type_code be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, type_node
        Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, type_code
    Otherwise:
        Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, "obj"
    End If

    Set line to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line, "\n"
    Return line
End Process

@Reasoning:
A type definition is "type Name = <body>". The body child is a record type, a
discriminated union (enum) type, a class, an interface (protocol) or a type
abbreviation. The name is in the type-definition node's value slot. We emit the
"type Name =" header then dispatch on the body kind.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_type_definition" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let indent_str be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let name be proc fs_value with node

    Let header be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_str, "type "
    Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, name
    Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, " ="

    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    If count is equal to 0:
        Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, "\n"
        Return header
    End If

    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let body be proc list_get from List with children, 0
    Let body_kind be proc fs_kind with body

    If body_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_RECORD_TYPE:
        Let rec_code be proc generate_record_type with ctx_ptr, body
        Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, rec_code
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
        Return result
    End If

    If body_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_ENUM_TYPE:
        Let union_code be proc generate_union_type with ctx_ptr, body
        Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, union_code
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
        Return result
    End If

    Note: abbreviation: the body is a type expression
    Let abbr be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, body
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, abbr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
An F# record type is "{ Field1 : T1; Field2 : T2 }". Each child is an
HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION carrying the field name in its value slot and the field
type as its first child. We render the brace-delimited semicolon-separated field
list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_record_type" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let fields be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    Let result be "{ "
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let field be proc list_get from List with fields, i
        Let fname be proc fs_value with field
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "; "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, fname
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " : "

        Let fcount be proc fs_child_count with field
        If fcount is greater than 0:
            Let fchildren be proc fs_children with field
            Let ftype be proc list_get from List with fchildren, 0
            Let ftype_code be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, ftype
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ftype_code
        Otherwise:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "obj"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " }"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
An F# discriminated union is "| Case1 | Case2 of T". Each child is an
HIR_VARIANT_DEFINITION carrying the case name in its value slot and an optional
payload type as its first child. Each case is emitted on its own indented line
as "| Name" or "| Name of T".
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_union_type" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let cases be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node
    Let result be ""

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let case be proc list_get from List with cases, i
        Let cname be proc fs_value with case

        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
        Let ci be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ci
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "| "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, cname

        Let ccount be proc fs_child_count with case
        If ccount is greater than 0:
            Let cchildren be proc fs_children with case
            Let payload be proc list_get from List with cchildren, 0
            Let payload_code be proc generate_type_expression with ctx_ptr, payload
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " of "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, payload_code
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A nested module/namespace is "module Name =" followed by its indented child
declarations. The HIR_MODULE node carries the module name in its value slot and
the contained declarations in its children list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_nested_module" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let indent_str be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let name be proc fs_value with node

    Let result be indent_str
    If name is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "module "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, name
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " =\n"
    Otherwise:
        Set result to ""
    End If

    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with node

    Let body_indent be 0
    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc indent with ctx_ptr
        Set body_indent to 1
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc list_get from List with children, i
        Let child_code be proc generate_declaration with ctx_ptr, child
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, child_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If body_indent is equal to 1:
        proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    End If

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The translation entry returns a HIR_MODULE root whose single child is the
translated program root (itself a HIR_MODULE for a multi-declaration file). We
walk the outermost module's declarations; if a declaration is itself a module
(the program-root wrapper), we recurse into its declarations so the flat F#
chunk emits the actual top-level declarations in source order.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_module" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx as FSharpCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return proc generate_module_body with ctx_ptr, ctx.hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits one module's declarations. A child that is itself a HIR_MODULE carrying no
name (the program-root wrapper the frontend inserts) is transparently flattened
by recursing into its declarations; a named nested module is emitted as a real
"module Name =" block via generate_declaration. This makes the wrapper invisible
in the output while preserving genuine nested modules.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_module_body" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, module_node as Integer returns String:
    If module_node is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let declarations be proc fs_children with module_node
    Let count be proc fs_child_count with module_node

    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let decl_kind be proc fs_kind with decl

        If decl_kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_MODULE:
            Let decl_name be proc fs_value with decl
            If decl_name is equal to 0:
                Note: anonymous program-root wrapper: flatten transparently
                Let inner be proc generate_module_body with ctx_ptr, decl
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, inner
            Otherwise:
                Let named be proc generate_declaration with ctx_ptr, decl
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, named
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Let decl_code be proc generate_declaration with ctx_ptr, decl
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, decl_code
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public entry used by the translation driver and the round-trip probe. Wraps the
create-context + generate-module pair so callers don't manage the context
lifecycle. The returned String holds the complete F# source.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_fsharp_code" takes hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx be proc create_codegen_context with hir_module
    Let code be proc generate_module with ctx
    Return code
End Process

@Reasoning:
Backward-compatible public name retained from the original backend interface:
the driver may call either hir_to_fsharp or generate_fsharp_code; both produce
the complete F# source string for the given HIR module root.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_to_fsharp" takes hir_root as Integer returns String:
    Return proc generate_fsharp_code with hir_root
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# operator / token spelling recovery
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Binary expressions carry the original F# lexer token id in their operator slot.
The F# lexer assigns small dense integer ids to its tokens; this cascade maps
the operator token ids to their F# infix spellings. The mapping covers
arithmetic, comparison, equality, logical, bitwise, the pipe operators (|> <|)
and the composition operators (>> <<). The token ids are the F# lexer's
published TOKEN_* constants, matched here by importing them so the spelling is
anchored to the exact ids the frontend wrote. The fallback returns "+" so an
unmapped operator degrades to syntactically valid F#.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fsharp_operator_spelling" takes token_id as Integer returns String:
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_PLUS from FSharpLexer:
        Return "+"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_MINUS from FSharpLexer:
        Return "-"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_MULTIPLY from FSharpLexer:
        Return "*"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_DIVIDE from FSharpLexer:
        Return "/"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_MODULO from FSharpLexer:
        Return "%"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_POWER from FSharpLexer:
        Return "**"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL from FSharpLexer:
        Return "="
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL from FSharpLexer:
        Return "<>"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_LESS_THAN from FSharpLexer:
        Return "<"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_THAN from FSharpLexer:
        Return ">"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL from FSharpLexer:
        Return "<="
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL from FSharpLexer:
        Return ">="
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_AND_OP from FSharpLexer:
        Return "&&"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_OR_OP from FSharpLexer:
        Return "||"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_RIGHT from FSharpLexer:
        Return "|>"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_LEFT from FSharpLexer:
        Return "<|"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_COMPOSE_RIGHT from FSharpLexer:
        Return ">>"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_COMPOSE_LEFT from FSharpLexer:
        Return "<<"
    End If
    If token_id is equal to TOKEN_STRING_CONCAT from FSharpLexer:
        Return "+"
    End If

    Return "+"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The for-loop iterator variable is stored as a raw F# lexer token; its name is
the token's text. Routing through the lexer's get_token_text accessor recovers
the source identifier exactly, so the emitted "for name in ..." matches the
original loop variable.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fsharp_token_text" takes token as Integer returns String:
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return "_"
    End If
    Let text be proc get_token_text from FSharpLexer with token
    If text is equal to 0:
        Return "_"
    End If
    Return text
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Diagnostics accessors
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Predicate accessor for the had_error sentinel; returns the raw 0/1 integer
because Boolean is Integer in the bootstrap layer. The driver consults this
after generation to decide whether to surface diagnostics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "had_codegen_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as FSharpCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.had_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the accumulated error-message list pointer so the driver can iterate
diagnostics; the list is owned by the context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_codegen_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as FSharpCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.errors
End Process
